This dataset shows Australian Ports in 2003. The data was sourced from the Lloyds Register Firplay, which publishes the Ports and Terminals Guide providing information on Ports and Facilites around the world. The spatial representation of this dataset was produced as part of the National Oceans Office National Marine Atlas showing the non-fisheries uses of Australia's marine jurisdiction.

The map shows Submarine Cables in Australia's Marine Jurisdiciton. The cables shown are those that extend more than three nautical miles offshore into Commonwealth waters, and include International cables and offshore cables connecting Australian cities. The main thematic data in the map was sourced from Australian Hydrographic Service Charts. The map was produced in 2003 for the National Marine Atlas - Non-fisheries Uses in Australia's Marine Jurisdiction, published by the National Oceans Office. Additional metadata for each layer are available (see 'Links').

rim:LocalizedString.value: There are currently fourteen (14) Australian properties on the World Heritage List. The Great Barrier Reef, the Tasmanian Wilderness, the Wet Tropics of Queensland and Shark Bay meet all four World Heritage criteria for natural heritage, with Kakadu National Park, Uluru-Kata Tjuta National Park, Willandra Lakes Region and the Tasmanian Wilderness being listed for both natural and cultural criteria. The Australian Fossil Mammal Sites (Naracoorte/Riversleigh), Lord Howe Island Group, Central Eastern Rainforest Reserves of Australia, Fraser Island, Macquarie Island, Heard and McDonald Islands, and the Greater Blue Mountains Area are listed under the World Heritage criteria for natural heritage. Each property is stored as a separate set of data. A single Australian World Heritage Areas database has been created by combining the data. All data are GDA compliant and use the WGS84 spheroid and datum. The coastal boundary for the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area is interim. This line is only INDICATIVE of "mean low tide", as stated in the World Heritage inscription. An appropriate caveat must accompany this data when used for analysis or map production.
